name: Project Hub x e@UBC Code Impact: Code for Social Change

owner.name: UBC Computer Science Student Society - CSSS

description:
Join Project Hub's FB Group: https://www.facebook.com/groups/1692464824398686/


Are you passionate about making a positive social, health or environment impact on the world using the power of code and technology? Are you interested on working for a startup project that will make a significant social impact? Or maybe you are interested in learning how to combine entrepreneurship with computer science and finding out what resources UBC has to offer for student entrepreneurs? If any of those ideals appealed to you, then come by Project Hub’s kickoff event featuring speakers Andrea Lloyd from e@UBC and Bryana Russell from Lean Launch Pad. Get ready for an engaging presentation on using tech for social good as well as an opportunity to work on Jooles, a startup project focused on female health. Refreshments will be provided, so see you there on Jan 13 at ICICS rm 014 from 5-7pm!



What is Jooles?
Jooles is a gameified, educational menstrual cycle charting app for young women aged 11-15. Some of the root causes of health issues later in life are the same conditions that cause distressing symptoms of hormone abnormalities in adolescence. We aim to educate women to understand their bodies, to encourage users identify patterns that could explain their health concerns, and engage youth in overcoming the taboos and discomfort that persists around women's cycles.

What is Social/Impact Venture?
Impact ventures are for-purpose organizations that focus on important local and global challenges with a strong emphasis on maximizing positive impact in areas such as social, health, and environment. e@UBC programs help venture teams discover and validate a business model that can achieve the purpose-driven mission while fueling financial sustainability and growth of the venture. Facilitators and mentors include entrepreneurs and executives that have experience working with impact-focused organizations.

http://entrepreneurship.ubc.ca/social-venture-stream/

name: AUS x UBC Filmsoc: Violent
description:
North of 49 Movies on Campus, UBC Arts Undergraduate Society, and UBC Film Society are excited to invite you to a free screening of the movie Violent.

Violent follows the story of Dagny, a young woman longing to escape her small-town life, and her reminiscences of the five people who loved her most all while experiencing a clear epiphany. Violent is the award-winning directorial debut of Andrew Huculiak, the drummer of Vancouver-based band We Are The City. The trailer can be viewed here: http://bit.ly/2cPYz2z

North of 49 Movies on Campus screenings are all FREE and do not require an RSVP! Free food and refreshments will also be available!

Future Screenings:

North of 49 Films on Campus is a series of Canadian movie screenings on campuses across the country with support from Telefilm Canada and Vancouver International FIlm Festival.

name: Law and Society Information Night!

UBC's Law and Society department is hosting an information night for students in the minor or students interested in program. Light refreshments will be provided!

Come meet professors in the LASO department! Meet with the LASO advisor, Professor Sindelar! Got a burning question about your LASO courseload you want answered? Here's your chance!

We have a great line-up of professors who will be joining the event!
- Renisa Mawani (SOCI), research in diaspora and colonial legal history, and author of Colonial Proximities (2009)

http://www.history.ubc.ca/people/arlene-sindelar

http://grsj.arts.ubc.ca/persons/mark-harris/

http://www.history.ubc.ca/people/bradley-miller

- Bruce Miller (ANTH), research into sociocultural anthropology, anthropology of law, and indigenous rights, and author of Oral History on Trial (2011)
http://anth.ubc.ca/faculty/bruce-miller/

- Carole Blackburn (ANTH), research into the relationship between indigenous peoples and settler states - rights, sovereignty, and political recognition, and author of Harvest of Souls (2004)
http://anth.ubc.ca/faculty/carole-blackburn/

Please reserve your spot with eventbrite! 

See you there!

name: Sex In All Languages
description:
THE IDEA 
Students of all cultures and sexual identities & orientations are invited to join us for a dialogue over dinner to share their experiences and perspectives on sex in a welcoming and inclusive space. Our aim is to expand our understanding of norms, expectations and practices around sex by encouraging a variety of voices to have a seat at the proverbial table.  After breaking the ice in our sex talk as a big group, participants can choose any topic that interest them for smaller, in-depth discussions. 

Sex in All Languages was developped in partnership between  UBC Equity Ambassadors, UBC Hua Dialogue, Global Lounge, UBC Intercultural Alliance, ACAM Dialogues, SAAM committee, Residence Life, and the Equity and Inclusion Office.
▼►▲◄ ▼►▲◄ ▼►▲◄ ▼►▲◄ ▼►▲◄ ▼►▲◄▼►▲◄▼►▲◄ 

TABLE TOPICS
1. Virginity and sexual debut, sex before or after marriage, first time experiences
2. LGBTQ, gender non-binary
3. Sexual norms in different cultures. Approach, initiation, and negotiation.
4. Consent and talking about sex in a healthy way
5. Interracial and intercultural relationship/sexual experience.
6. Your sexual journey. First-time and starting off, body image, sexual desire, developing your sexual identity, fetish/BDSM/kink.

▼►▲◄ ▼►▲◄ ▼►▲◄ ▼►▲◄ ▼►▲◄ ▼►▲◄▼►▲◄▼►▲◄

name: Vancouver Access Makeathon: Info Session
description:
UBC Women in Engineering and Young WiSE are excited to host an info session on January 10th from 5-6pm in Kaiser Room 2020/2030 for this years Vancouver Access Makeathon.

In partnership with Rick Hansen Foundation, SFU’s School of Interactive Arts and Technology, TechSoup NetSquared, Tom Global, UBC Women in Engineering, and UBC Young Women in Engineering and Science, the Neil Squire Society is organizing a 48 hour event called the Access Makeathon from January 27th to 29th, 2017.

Over 48 hours, a person with a disability (MAKER) will connect with a team of makers (YOU) who will build open source assistive technology that will directly address a need the person has. It is an opportunity for makers to apply their knowledge and skills to address a real world need of a person. The goal is each team will help a person leave the event with a working prototype that improves their quality of life.

Please come to out to the info session on January 10th to meet a representative from the Neil Squire Society and a 'MAKER' to learn more about the event and ask any questions you may have before registering.

Please hit 'going' above to RSVP for the info session and head over to the Neil Squire Society link (https://www.eventbrite.com/e/access-makeathon-vancouver-2016-tickets-3473530423) to register for the Access Makeathon. Light refreshments will be provided! Hope to see you there.
